Stepkids not steroids.

I don't know what to do anymore. Hold on? To what exactly? The fire Marshall didn't even have the inkling to tell me they were condemning what was my home. My heart hurts. I can't even look my firstborn in the face without feeling the urge to die before him. I want to cry so bad.

Now 8 years later at 32 years old. I started a family and figured it was all behind me. But fate had its own plans for me. Here I sit in the ruins of what I hoped to be a plentiful future. Homeless again. In the middle of a snowstorm and a pandemic with my little family.
I feel defeated. I wanna give up soo bad. I can't now. But I have nothing left but my 5 month old son, my steroids both 7 and 5 and their mother. As we try to hold strong during this trying time.

8 years ago I was homeless. I was sleeping in a park and had to find different places to sleep around the park to avoid arrest or worse. I finally found a job, saved up every penny to pay for small place just to rest my head for a few months. I weighed 114 lbs.

And before you ask. No I do not have any cash but what the red cross offered which was a $800 prepaid card. I do not own a car as our last one was totaled on my way to my stepkids school and an anxious driver couldn't tell red from green. It's currently storming out.
